This is the code used to pre-process the data in order to evaluate proposed DNN architectures. Due to being written in Jupyter Notebook different parts of the code can be run without needing all of the previous parts to be run as well.

The code was written by Georgios Anyfantis

The first piece of code is used to import the libraries that will be used to pre-process the data and to build the model.

This part of the code imports all the files that contain the CIC-IDS-2017 dataset. The files are from the MachineLearningCVE. The whole dataset can be downloaded from here.

Although, it should be noted that this is the link to the paper published with the dataset. The link for the dataset is at the bottom of that page, web page was last accessed in 28/04/2022.

In this section, the invalid values are detected and the affected rows are removed from the files. Finally, they are concantinated to a larger pandas file that contains the entire dataset.

The files are inputted in chronological order.

Removal of constant features is important to not affect the use of ANOVA for feature reduction as it may affect the ranking of the features.

Additionally, these features do not contain any information that can be useful for the model, as all values are constant or they vary very little, thus they may generate noise that can damage the accuracy of the model.

This method finds the features that are constant and returns a list with them.

# Similar method to the previous one, main difference is that it removes the all the 
# features except the ones in the list
# mainly used for ANOVA feature reduction

def new_dataset(dataset, anova_res):
    train_output = dataset

    for anova_column in range(len(anova_res)):
        print(anova_res[anova_column])
        # Removing the feature from the inputted dataset
        dataset = dataset.drop(anova_res[anova_column], axis=1)

    # Dropping the remaining features
    train_output = train_output.drop(dataset.columns, axis=1)

    return train_output

def new_dataset_remove(dataset, anova_res):

    for anova_column in range(len(anova_res)):
        print(anova_res[anova_column])
        # Removing the feature from the inputted dataset
        dataset = dataset.drop(anova_res[anova_column], axis=1)

    return dataset

The method used to apply ANOVA test and return a different number of features depending the requirements.

In [ ]:
def selectKBest(train, test, valid, k):
  sel = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=k)  # k is the number of columns to be returned from this function

  # preparing the data for the application of ANOVA
  y_train = train.iloc[:, [-1]]
  X_train = train.drop(y_train.columns, axis=1)

  y_test = test.iloc[:, [-1]]
  X_test = test.drop(y_test.columns, axis=1)
      
  y_valid = valid.iloc[:, [-1]]
  X_valid = valid.drop(y_valid.columns, axis=1)

  # Performing ANOVA F-test
  sel.fit_transform(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())
  sel.transform(X_test)
  sel.transform(X_valid)

  mask = sel.get_support()
  new_features = []  # The list of your K best features

  # creating the list of the selected features
  for bool, feature in zip(mask, train.columns):
    if bool:
      new_features.append(feature)

  return new_features

In [ ]:
# Method used to ensure that the name is the feature file
# to match the ones in the dataframes
# as to ensure feature reduction is performed

def correct_names(columns, orig):
  col = []
  for m in range(len(orig)):
    for n in range(len(columns)):
      if columns[n].replace(" ", "") == orig[m].replace(" ", ""):
        col.append(columns[m])

  return col

# The method used to create the initial architecture,
# All layers are seen in the method with their respective values
# These are reflected in the figure in the Appendix

def create_baseline():
	model = Sequential()
	model.add(Dense(128, input_dim=36, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(16, activation='softmax'))
	model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
	return model

                        verbose=1,
                        restore_best_weights=True)

# Method used to print the confusion matrices of each class
# Code modified from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/62722416/plot-confusion-matrix-for-multilabel-classifcation-python

def print_confusion_matrices(confusion_matrix, axes, class_label, class_names, fontsize=14):

    # Creating a dataframe with the confusion matrix of each class
    df_confusion = pd.DataFrame(
        confusion_matrix, index=class_names, columns=class_names,
    )

    # Generating the heatmaps for each value of the confusion matrix
    # of the inputted class
    try:
        heat_map = sns.heatmap(df_confusion, annot=True, fmt="d", cbar=False, ax=axes)
    except ValueError:
        raise ValueError("Confusion matrix values must be integers.")

    heat_map.yaxis.set_ticklabels(heat_map.yaxis.get_ticklabels(), rotation=0, ha='right', fontsize=fontsize)
    heat_map.xaxis.set_ticklabels(heat_map.xaxis.get_ticklabels(), rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=fontsize)
    axes.set_ylabel('True label')
    axes.set_xlabel('Predicted label')
    axes.set_title("Confusion Matrix for the class - " + class_label)

# The method used to construct the third architecture tested

def create_baseline_3():
	model = Sequential()
	model.add(Dense(256, input_dim=36, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
	return model

# This method is used to generate the model using the fifth architecture
# All the layers and their configurations can be seen below
# As well as the loss function used and optimizer

def create_baseline_5():
	model = Sequential()
	model.add(Dense(512, input_dim=36, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(256, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(128, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))

# The method used to generate the Improved initial architecture
# without output layer

def create_baseline_32end():
	model = Sequential()
	model.add(Dense(128, input_dim=36, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu'))
	model.add(Dropout(0.2))
	model.add(Dense(32, activation='softmax'))
	model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
	return model
